                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>until <date>2d night</date>\n                <add>?</add> to keep it from<lb/> the public eye, when on that night at<lb/> his\n                boarding house he was so intox<lb/>-icated that he was compelled to leave<lb/> the\n                table where the recital of the prayers<lb/> were going on <add>?</add> was\n                annoying<lb/> to those around him. He must there<lb/>-fore have obtained his liquor\n                at a pub<lb/>-lic house &amp; therefore partook of <hi rend=\"underline\"\n                    >Homity</hi><add>?</add><lb/> His host &amp; Hostess, not wishing to injure<lb/>\n                him suffered this dereliction, to remain<lb/> within themselves under the\n                promise<lb/> that he would leave their house, as<lb/> it was impossible to board him\n                longer<lb/> &amp; thus I as well as the people were<lb/> kept unacquainted with this\n                vice<lb/> until after <persName>Mr. Jacobs</persName> resignation as Hazan<lb/> when\n                I called upon him to read<lb/> the Law, presuming that he was a pro<lb/>=per person,\n                &amp; he did read on <date>Sabbath</date><lb/> when those who were acquainted<lb/>\n                murmured strongly &amp; loudly when it<lb/> reached my ears, of course no blame<lb/>\n                could be attached to me, as I then<lb/> was only made acquainted of his<lb/>\n                weakness to call it by a gentle name<lb/> of course some action was requisite<lb/>\n                &amp; I did not allow him to read again</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3sx64w6x/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
            }
